  .abstract
    %p The RaspberryPi is a small, affordable computer that you can use for your Internet of Things projects. It's incredibly simple to use if you have a basic understanding of circuits and how computers work. I'll give an overview on how to set up a project with resources for the fundamental steps along the way. 

    %p I'd like to show my journey into setting up a light sensor that became an increasingly dense project as I went along. Show the trouble of thinking something worked one way and finding out it worked a completely different way. Converting analogue to digital and other frankenstein-ing of hardware, sensors, and microchips. 

    %p If the talk is accepted the format will be as follows: 

    %ul
      %li Basics of RaspberryPi, OS, and components
      %li How Ruby interfaces with everything
      %li How to do the research for types of sensors and components that you will need. 
      %li Wrap up with questions and give away 2 RaspberryPis. One to grea question. One to great project idea. 

    %p The goal is to show that the RaspberryPi is a hands-on model for computing that is educational, powerful, and fun.

  .bio
    %p I am the General Manager of Cloud City Development. I have ten years of experience bringing quality digital products to life. My focus is on how well design and development works together for the good of the end-user and company goals. I've created and worked alongside many successful startups including 12 Spokes, CrowdFlower, Gengo, and Kanjiru. I believe design is both an art and science. My specialties include product design, LeanUX, agile, customer development, and hardware hacking.

